<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="124" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="29.[828,1437,190,629]" pageId="29" pageNumber="124">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,937,382,405]" pageId="29" pageNumber="124">Remarks.</emphasis>
This group holds some species placed previously in 
<emphasis box="[886,1012,415,438]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="124">Tenuicomus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="CHANDLER D. S. &amp; UHMANN G. &amp; NARDI G. &amp; TELNOV D." box="[1028,1262,414,437]" pageId="29" pageNumber="124" pagination="421 - 455" refId="ref52747" refString="CHANDLER D. S., UHMANN G., NARDI G. &amp; TELNOV D. 2008: Family Anthicidae Latreille, 1819. Pp. 421 - 455. In: LOBL I. &amp; SMETANA A. (eds): Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera. Volume 5. Tenebrionoidea. Apollo Books, Stenstrup, 670 pp." type="book chapter" year="2008">CHANDLER et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
, as 
<emphasis box="[1305,1421,414,437]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="124">Tenuicollis</emphasis>
). They resemble members of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Chevrolat" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[1161,1280,446,470]" class="Insecta" family="Anthicidae" genus="Microhoria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciata">
<emphasis box="[1161,1280,446,470]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="124">M. fasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kejval &amp; Chandler" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Pic" baseAuthorityYear="1898" class="Insecta" family="Anthicidae" genus="Microhoria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schimperi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="124">M. schimperi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
groups based on characters of the mesoventrite and the male elytral apices, but differ by the reduced submarginal setose impressions of the metaventrite and abdominal sternum III, and by characters of the aedeagus (endophallic armature and position of the gonopore).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
